{"source_key":"sha256-d1b343ed42a51085ffb3fbb074863c4f","record_index":2699,"record_hash":"sha256:507743d7b65f842daa252aa60e50c4e3ff1106c55eeb3926a842a741d9582002","timestamp":"2026-06-04T22:06:52.205Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"The strongest signal is not “they hit errors.” It’s “they never got activated into a full GitButler workflow.”\n\nI defined:\n\n- **Starter:** first observed `Cli` event with `command='commit'` and `agent` set.\n- **Retained:** same `distinct_id` does another agentic `commit` in days 7-13.\n- Window: last 180 days, excluding the last 14 days so next-week retention is mature.\n- Caveat: this is “first observed in 180 days,” not guaranteed first-ever.\n\n**Main Finding**\nAgentic committers who churn mostly look like shallow/partial users:\n\n- low command volume\n- low command breadth\n- no `rub`\n- no `push`\n- often no `branchNew`\n- basically “agent made a commit-ish attempt, but did not complete the GitButler loop”\n\nThe sharpest cut:\n\n| First-week pattern | Users | Next-week retained |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| `branchNew` + `rub` + `push` | 247 | **64.4%** |\n| `rub` + `push` | 67 | **40.3%** |\n| `rub`, no push | 170 | **35.9%** |\n| push, no `rub` | 67 | **20.9%** |\n| no `rub`, no push | 113 | **16.8%** |\n\nSo the product question is probably: **how do we get first-time agentic committers from “commit happened” to “branch/change movement/push happened”?**\n\n**Agent Differences**\nAgent matters, but less than activation:\n\n- Codex: 48.9% retained\n- Claude Code: 42.4%\n- Cursor CLI: 34.0%\n\nCodex looks a bit better, Cursor CLI worse, but the bigger gap is workflow completion. Claude users still retain well when they hit branch + rub + push.\n\n**Errors**\nErrors are not a simple churn driver.\n\nRetained users had *more* errors in week one, because they did way more work. First-week `rub` error incidence was 67.1% for retained users vs 42.7% for churned users. That does not mean errors help; it means active users hit more edges.\n\nBut there is still one actionable error pattern: **stale/invalid file IDs.** In 0.20.0, Claude Code `commit` event error rate looked terrifying at event level, but it was dominated by one user producing 97.3% of Claude’s commit error events. The repeated error was basically invalid file IDs like stale `s0 t0 u0...` IDs. User-level error incidence was similar across agents: around 33-36%.\n\n**What I’d Fix**\n1. **Agent skill should optimize for activation, not just committing.**  \n   After first commit success, the skill should naturally steer toward `but push` / PR when appropriate, and toward explicit commands like `move`, `amend`, `stage`, `uncommit` rather than vague `rub`.\n\n2. **Add a hard loop-breaker for invalid IDs.**  \n   If an agent sees “Invalid file ID(s) … Run `but status`,” it should not retry IDs. It should run `but status -fv`, re-read IDs, and only then retry. This should be in the skill, and ideally the CLI hint should be agent-explicit.\n\n3. **Track activation as a product metric.**  \n   I’d add/monitor: first agentic commit → first-week `branchNew`[REDACTED:path] command → `push`. That activation path predicts retention much better than raw error rate.\n\n4. **Do not overreact to `rub` usage.**  \n   `rub` currently correlates with retention because it means the agent is doing real GitButler workflow work. Still worth steering agents to specific commands where possible, but don’t just suppress `rub` blindly.\n\n5. **0.20.0 retention can’t be judged yet.**  \n   It has fresh error data, but not a complete next-week retention window. For 0.20.0 specifically, the thing to watch now is invalid-ID loops, especially Claude Code.\n\nMy take: churn is less “GitButler broke” and more “the agent never crossed the activation threshold.” The best bet is to make the skill and CLI recovery paths push agents through a complete branch/change/push workflow, and aggressively stop stale-ID retry loops.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-04T22:06:52.205Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}